<doc id="221525" wikidata="Q1952404" url="?curid=221525" title="Multilinear map">
<text>In linear algebra, a multilinear map is a function of several variables that is linear separately in each variable. More precisely, a multilinear map is a function

:formula_1

where formula_2 (formula_3) and formula_4 are vector spaces (or modules over a commutative ring), with the following property: for each formula_5, if all of the variables but formula_6 are held constant, then formula_7 is a linear function of formula_6. One way to visualize this is to imagine two orthogonal vectors; if one of these vectors is scaled by a factor of 2 while the other remains unchanged, the cross product likewise scales by a factor of two. If both are scaled by a factor of 2, the cross product scales by a factor of formula_9.

A multilinear map of one variable is a linear map, and of two variables is a bilinear map. More generally, for any nonnegative integer formula_10, a multilinear map of &quot;k&quot; variables is called a &quot;k&quot;-linear map. If the codomain of a multilinear map is the field of scalars, it is called a multilinear form. Multilinear maps and multilinear forms are fundamental objects of study in multilinear algebra.

If all variables belong to the same space, one can consider symmetric, antisymmetric and alternating &quot;k&quot;-linear maps. The latter two coincide if the underlying ring (or field) has a characteristic different from two, else the former two coincide.

==Examples==
* Any bilinear map is a multilinear map. For example, any inner product on a formula_11-vector space is a multilinear map, as is the cross product of vectors in formula_12.
* The determinant of a matrix is an alternating multilinear function of the columns (or rows) of a square matrix.
* If formula_13 is a &quot;Ck&quot; function, then the formula_10th derivative of formula_15 at each point formula_16 in its domain can be viewed as a symmetric formula_10-linear function formula_18.

