==De Rham theorem==

Stokes&#x27; theorem is an expression of duality between de Rham cohomology and the homology of chains. It says that the pairing of differential forms and chains, via integration, gives a homomorphism from de Rham cohomology formula_3 to singular cohomology groups formula_33 de Rham&#x27;s theorem, proved by Georges de Rham in 1931, states that for a smooth manifold , this map is in fact an isomorphism.

More precisely, consider the map

:formula_34

defined as follows: for any formula_35, let be the element of formula_36 that acts as follows:

:formula_37

The theorem of de Rham asserts that this is an isomorphism between de Rham cohomology and singular cohomology.

The exterior product endows the direct sum of these groups with a ring structure. A further result of the theorem is that the two cohomology rings are isomorphic (as graded rings), where the analogous product on singular cohomology is the cup product.

==Sheaf-theoretic de Rham isomorphism==
For any smooth manifold &quot;M&quot;, let formula_38 be the constant sheaf on &quot;M&quot; associated to the abelian group formula_39; in other words, formula_38 is the sheaf of locally constant real-valued functions on &quot;M.&quot; Then we have a natural isomorphism

:formula_41

between the de Rham cohomology and the sheaf cohomology of formula_38. (Note that this shows that de Rham cohomology may also be computed in terms of Čech cohomology; indeed, since every smooth manifold is paracompact Hausdorff we have that sheaf cohomology is isomorphic to the Čech cohomology formula_43 for any good cover formula_44 of &quot;M&quot;.)

===Proof===
The standard proof proceeds by showing that the de Rham complex, when viewed as a complex of sheaves, is an acyclic resolution of formula_38. In more detail, let &quot;m&quot; be the dimension of &quot;M&quot; and let formula_46 denote the sheaf of germs of formula_47-forms on &quot;M&quot; (with formula_48 the sheaf of formula_49 functions on &quot;M&quot;). By the Poincaré lemma, the following sequence of sheaves is exact (in the abelian category of sheaves):

:formula_50

This long exact sequence now breaks up into short exact sequences of sheaves

:formula_51

where by exactness we have isomorphisms formula_52 for all &quot;k&quot;. Each of these induces a long exact sequence in cohomology. Since the sheaf formula_48 of formula_49 functions on &quot;M&quot; admits partitions of unity, any formula_48-module is a fine sheaf; in particular, the sheaves formula_46 are all fine. Therefore, the sheaf cohomology groups formula_57 vanish for formula_58 since all fine sheaves on paracompact spaces are acyclic. So the long exact cohomology sequences themselves ultimately separate into a chain of isomorphisms. At one end of the chain is the sheaf cohomology of formula_38 and at the other lies the de Rham cohomology.

==Related ideas==
The de Rham cohomology has inspired many mathematical ideas, including Dolbeault cohomology, Hodge theory, and the Atiyah–Singer index theorem. However, even in more classical contexts, the theorem has inspired a number of developments. Firstly, the Hodge theory proves that there is an isomorphism between the cohomology consisting of harmonic forms and the de Rham cohomology consisting of closed forms modulo exact forms. This relies on an appropriate definition of harmonic forms and of the Hodge theorem. For further details see Hodge theory.

===Harmonic forms===

If is a compact Riemannian manifold, then each equivalence class in formula_60 contains exactly one harmonic form. That is, every member formula_13 of a given equivalence class of closed forms can be written as

:formula_62

where formula_63 is exact and formula_64 is harmonic: formula_65.

Any harmonic function on a compact connected Riemannian manifold is a constant. Thus, this particular representative element can be understood to be an extremum (a minimum) of all cohomologously equivalent forms on the manifold. For example, on a -torus, one may envision a constant -form as one where all of the &quot;hair&quot; is combed neatly in the same direction (and all of the &quot;hair&quot; having the same length). In this case, there are two cohomologically distinct combings; all of the others are linear combinations. In particular, this implies that the 1st Betti number of a -torus is two. More generally, on an formula_7-dimensional torus formula_67, one can consider the various combings of formula_68-forms on the torus. There are formula_7 choose formula_68 such combings that can be used to form the basis vectors for formula_71; the formula_68-th Betti number for the de Rham cohomology group for the formula_7-torus is thus formula_7 choose formula_68.

More precisely, for a differential manifold , one may equip it with some auxiliary Riemannian metric. Then the Laplacian formula_76 is defined by

:formula_77
with formula_2 the exterior derivative and formula_79 the codifferential. The Laplacian is a homogeneous (in grading) linear differential operator acting upon the exterior algebra of differential forms: we can look at its action on each component of degree formula_68 separately.

If formula_81 is compact and oriented, the dimension of the kernel of the Laplacian acting upon the space of -forms is then equal (by Hodge theory) to that of the de Rham cohomology group in degree formula_68: the Laplacian picks out a unique harmonic form in each cohomology class of closed forms. In particular, the space of all harmonic formula_68-forms on formula_81 is isomorphic to formula_33 The dimension of each such space is finite, and is given by the formula_68-th Betti number.

===Hodge decomposition===
Let formula_81 be a compact oriented Riemannian manifold. The &quot;Hodge decomposition&quot; states that any formula_68-form on formula_81 uniquely splits into the sum of three components:

:formula_90

where formula_63 is exact, formula_92 is co-exact, and formula_64 is harmonic.

One says that a form formula_92 is co-closed if formula_95 and co-exact if formula_96 for some form formula_97, and that formula_64 is harmonic if the Laplacian is zero, formula_65. This follows by noting that exact and co-exact forms are orthogonal; the orthogonal complement then consists of forms that are both closed and co-closed: that is, of harmonic forms. Here, orthogonality is defined with respect to the inner product on formula_100:

:formula_101

By use of Sobolev spaces or distributions, the decomposition can be extended for example to a complete (oriented or not) Riemannian manifold.

